The paper deals with problems in computational geometry and combinatorics, specifically the maximum independent set of rectangles problem and the geometric knapsack problem. These problems involve the manipulation and selection of geometric objects, which falls under the purview of computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of parameterized algorithms and approximation algorithms suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The study of approximation ratios and complexity classes such as W[1]-hardness suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the use of optimization techniques and analysis of algorithms suggests a connection to game theory (cs.GT).
